tweet: The mitigation is to use ‚Äúpoint in time‚Äù or ‚Äúbitemporal‚Äù databases which record each revision as a new entry ‚Äî they‚Äôre called bitemporal because they record both the timestamp of the revision, and the timestamp that the revision refers to. It‚Äôs more work but it‚Äôs worth it.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: It can even happen with market data (eg closing prices or settlement prices can be revised) although it‚Äôs less common and usually less impactful.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: Similar things occur in company financials which can often be revised (either by the company or by the data vendor, who may have initially published an incorrect value) or essentially any fundamental data, including analyst forecasts.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: But if you just pull a time series of quarterly US GDP from eg Bloomberg, you will get the final estimates ‚Äî if you key these against the January release dates then you have two months of look-ahead in your model!
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: You are a careful quant researcher so you know to key the GDP data agains release dates and not naively assume that it was available at the end of the quarter.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: Take US GDP as an example. The ‚Äúadvance‚Äù estimate for US Q4 GDP is released at the end of January. There is then a ‚Äúpreliminary‚Äù release at the end of Feb and a ‚Äúfinal‚Äù release at the end of March.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: Or if using binned data, you can form your signal at the end of each bin and then assume execution at the VWAP (or closing price) for the next bin. For high frequency strategies it means correctly modelling the latency of your orders being sent to market.  More tomorrow!
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: To mitigate, you need to make sure your signal is formed *before* the price you intend to trade at is observed. That might mean forming the signal 30 minutes before the close if you intend to trade in the closing auction.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: This particularly affects mean reversion strategies, which look great if you assume you can observe the close and then trade there - I won't explain why but you should be able to figure it out.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: (b) by definition you can't trade after the close, because the market is closed! The next opportunity you get to trade will be the open of the next session, when the price could be *very* different.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: The very worst form of this bias is when you observe a closing price and assume you can trade at that price. It's so bad because (a) the closing price is often quite distorted - a lot of flow happens just before the close and it can move the close away from fair value, and ...
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: If you are trading only infrequently then it likely takes some time to work your order in the market. The price you get will be closer to the VWAP over the period you execute the order than to the price you observed before you sent the order.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: If you are trading very frequently, the chance that the price moves while your order is being sent to the market is higher (future price moves will most likely be correlated with the direction of your orders so the price moves away from you more often than not)
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: ... often people convince themselves that it's a very benign form of look-ahead, and probably won't materially affect the backtest results.  That *might* be true, it depends on the strategy. But most often it's not.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: This is hard to get 100% right and the only way to be sure is to collect as much data yourself as possible, and be extremely careful /skeptical about any data you didn‚Äôt collect yourself (eg stress test it by introducing additional lag and see if the signal survives)
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: For high frequency strategies it‚Äôs easy to introduce lookahead if you don‚Äôt model latency correctly (eg you assume it is lower than it really is, or you assume a constant latency when really it is stochastic).
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: This is particularly tough if you are buying data from someone rather than collecting it yourself, because you don‚Äôt only need to check you are using it correctly, you need to trust that the vendor didn‚Äôt introduce some lookahead by being sloppy or overly optimistic.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: This can be subtle, eg some alternative data provider has a dataset which is available before the open *now* but in the past it was only available after the open (or wasn‚Äôt available at all because the data vendor didn‚Äôt even exist)
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: Other examples include assuming some external dataset is available earlier than it really would be, eg available before the open when in reality it arrives during the trading day, or assuming it arrives during the trading day when in reality it arrives only after the close.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: For example, you are testing a mean reversion strategy on European stocks and you compute the signal with -(r - mean(r)).shift(1). If the stock exchanges in the sample close at different times, you are leaking information from the later closes into the earlier ones.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: Day 2. Look ahead in your signals.   This covers any form of using future information to decide what trade to make. There are lots of ways this can creep into your backtest.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: @H1Whe Either use a moving threshold (eg % of total market cap) or make it relative (eg stocks above 25th percentile of market cap across all live stocks on a given date). It only really matters for long term backtests. I am typically using last 3-10 years so I use constant values.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: Typically you need to be even more careful than that, since stocks could be delisted or subject to mergers/takeovers etc intra-month and they need to be removed from the universe. But the rolling universe selection gets rid of the look ahead.  More tomorrow!
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: The right thing to do is use a rolling universe selection ‚Äî every month (for example) you pick stocks that  meet your criteria, and they form the trading universe for the next month. At the end of the month, you need to pick again, dropping some stocks and admitting new ones.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: A more subtle mistake is to select stocks that met the volume/market cap criteria *at any point in history*. This is better, but you are still using future information ‚Äî a stock that doesn‚Äôt meet the criteria at t but does at T will generally increase in price between t and T.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: If your strategy is net long, this will flatter the backtest because you‚Äôve introduced a spurious upward drift in the prices of stocks in your universe.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: The most obvious way to mess this up is to select the assets that meet those criteria *today*. By definition, stocks with large market cap today were successful in the past (that‚Äôs how they got a large market cap). So you are using future information to pick stocks that did well.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx

tweet: Day 1. Look ahead when picking the trading universe.   You want a set of stocks/futures/coins/whatever to include in your backtest which meet some sensible criteria for market cap, liquidity, average daily volume etc.
name: cephalopod_v7_no_ftx_final_2.xlsx
